import math

Middle of Canister Temperature¶

In [2]:
def Temperature_middle(T1,Q,K1,r1,L):
    """This function solves for the temperature at the center of a nuclear waste canister given the temperature of the inner surfaces of the canister and accounting for conduction through the waste material

    Parameters
        ~Description
        ~Units
    ----------
    
    T1 :  float
        ~Temperature of the inner surface of the canister
        ~Kelvin
   
    Q : float
        ~Heat flow from heat generated from waste at centerline of canister. Sometimes shown in equations over the volume of the cylinder so it gives heat flow per unit volume
        ~Watts
   
    r1 : float
        ~radius from center of canister to inner surface
        ~meters
        
    L : float
        ~Length or height of cylinder canister
        ~meters
   
    K1 :  float
        ~Thermal conductivity constant corresponding to waste material 
        ~(Watts) / (Meters^2 * Kelvin)
   
    Returns
    -------
    float
        Temperature at the middle of the waste canister

    """
    Tm = T1 + (((Q / (math.pi * r1 ** 2 * (L))) * (r1 ** 2)) / (4 * K1)) 
    #Second part of equation accounts for conduction through the waste material
    return Tm

Inner Surface Temperature¶

In [6]:
def Temperature_inner_surface(T2,Q,r1,r2,L,K2):
    """This function solves for the temperature at the center of a nuclear waste canister given the ambient temperature surrounding the canister, the temperatures of the inner and outer surfaces of the canister

    Parameters
        ~Description
        ~Units
    ----------
   
    T2 : float
        ~Temperature of the outer surface of the canister
        ~Kelvin
        
    Q : float
        ~Heat flow from heat generated from waste at centerline of canister. Sometimes shown in equations over the volume of the cylinder so it gives heat flow per unit volume
        ~Watts
        
    r2 :  float
        ~radius from center of canister to outer surface
        ~meters
        
    r1 : float
        ~radius from center of canister to inner surface
        ~meters
        
    L : float
        ~Length or height of cylinder canister
        ~meters
        
    K2 : float
        ~Thermal conductivity constant corresponding to canister material
        ~(Watts) / (Meters^2 * Kelvin)
   
    Returns
    -------
    float
        Temperature at the inner surface of the waste canister

    """
    
    T1 = T2 + ((Q * math.log(r2 / r1)) / (2 * math.pi * L * K2)) 
    #Second half of the equation accounts for conduction through the thick canister
    return T1

Outer Surface Temperature¶

In [10]:
def Temperature_outer_surface(T0,r2,h0,Q,L,r1):
    """This function solves for the temperature at the center of a nuclear waste canister given the ambient temperature surrounding the canister, the temperatures of the inner and outer surfaces of the canister

    Parameters
        ~Description
        ~Units
    ----------
    
    T0 : float
        ~Ambient temperature around canister
        ~Kelvin
        
    Q : float
        ~Heat flow from heat generated from waste at centerline of canister. Sometimes shown in equations over the volume of the cylinder so it gives heat flow per unit volume
        ~Watts
        
    r2 :  float
        ~radius from center of canister to outer surface
        ~meters
        
    L : float
        ~Length or height of cylinder canister
        ~meters
        
    h0 : float
        ~Heat transfer coefficient corresponding to the outer surface temperature and ambient temperature
        ~(Watts) / (Meters^2 * Kelvin)

    Returns
    -------
    float
        Temperature at the outer surface of the waste canister

    """

    T2 = T0 + ((r2 * (Q / (math.pi * r1 ** 2 * (L)))) / (2 * h0)) 
    #T0 is a given quantity
    #The rest of the equation is accounting for heat convection from canister surface to surrounding air
    return T2

Middle Temperature Condensed¶

In [14]:
def Temperature_middle_final(T0,r2,h0,Q,L,r1,K2,K1):
    """This function solves for the temperature at the center of a nuclear waste canister given the ambient temperature surrounding the canister, the temperatures of the inner and outer surfaces of the canister

    Parameters
        ~Description
        ~Units
    ----------       
    T0 : float
        ~Ambient temperature around canister
        ~Kelvin
        
    Q : float
        ~Heat flow from heat generated from waste at centerline of canister. Sometimes shown in equations over the volume of the cylinder so it gives heat flow per unit volume
        ~Watts
        
    r2 :  float
        ~radius from center of canister to outer surface
        ~meters
        
    r1 : float
        ~radius from center of canister to inner surface
        ~meters
        
    L : float
        ~Length or height of cylinder canister
        ~meters
        
    K2 : float
        ~Thermal conductivity constant corresponding to canister material
        ~(Watts) / (Meters^2 * Kelvin)
        
    K1 :  float
        ~Thermal conductivity constant corresponding to waste material 
        ~(Watts) / (Meters^2 * Kelvin)
        
    h0 : float
        ~Heat transfer coefficient corresponding to the outer surface temperature and ambient temperature
        ~(Watts) / (Meters^2 * Kelvin)

    Returns
    -------
    float
        Temperature at the center of the waste canister

    """
    #Ambient temperature is given and used to find T2;
    # Then T1 is solved for using T2.
    # Tm is then solved for using T1 which gives Tmf
    T2 = Temperature_outer_surface(T0,r2,h0,Q,L,r1)
    T1 = Temperature_inner_surface(T2,Q,r1,r2,L,K2)
    Tmf = Temperature_middle(T1,Q,K1,r1,L)
    return Tmf

A Fuel Cycle Evaluation and Screening Study was done that analyzed the theoretical waste materials produced from a Molten Salt Reactor. By applying the different decay speeds of the various isotopes contained in the waste material, the total heat generation of the waste at different times can be measured. The following heat values correspond to the total heat generated at 10 years according to the study, but the amount of waste in each canister was varied in each leading to the change in values that you see below. The amount of waste per catainer in kg that will be analyzed in this study is 500 kg, 1000 kg, and 1500 kg. The given value for the total heat generated in 10 years was:

1177998.74 W/100GWe-y

This value was converted to W/canister for use in this study

Wasteform ideally needs to remain a solid "WHY?", therefore you can see what the temperature will be at the respective thermal conductivity. In the above example, tellurite glass is well below its melting point which is desirable.

The following waste materials were studied in depth and their melting points and thermal conductivities are listed below. These thermal conductivities will be used to calculate the centerline temperature at different times in the waste material. Three graphs will be plotted showing how the centerline temperatures change over time. Different wasteforms will be plotted on the same graph so that differences in their trends will be easily identifiable.

Important Note: The following graphs will only show the curves corresponding to sodalite and aluminosilicate waste forms as these waste materials had the highest and lowest thermal conductivities respectively out of the waste materials analyzed in this study. All of the curves for the other waste materials will fall in between these values. This was done to make the graph easier to intepret.

Canister Dimension Affect¶

How does the canister size affect the dissipation of heat throughout the system? Three canisters with varying radii will be analyzed. 'Canister dimension values obtained from Milos Atz's dissertation 2019' r1 is the radius to the inner surface of the canister r2 is the radius to the outer surface of the canister Canister thickness = .075 m

r2 = 0.23   # m

As the canister size increases, the amount of waste in the canister must also increase because this study assumes that the canister is full at all times. To make sure this is the case, we must use the following equation and apply it for each canister size:

(Initial given heat values) (W) x (Volume of Canister A, B, or C) (M^3) / (Volume of reference canister) (M^3) = (Heat generated by Canister A, B, or C) (W)

-The initial values have been used throughout this study and will be denoted by Qb. -Canisters A, B, and C are the different canister sizes being analyzed in this study -The reference canister refers to the canister dimensions that have been used throughtout this study.

This equation will take the amount of heat generarted by the waste in the reference canister, and convert it to the amount of heat generated by the waste in each different canister (A, B, and C), assuming the canisters are full.

Parametric Equations¶

There are lots of unknowns for molten salt reactor waste management. The fuel salt is molten in the reactor and salts are soluble in water, so spent fuel salt will need to be immobilized prior to disposal. However, no one has made any decisions about:

  1. The material in which waste salt will be immobilized;
  2. The relative amounts of waste and immobilizer in the mixture (e.g. 30% waste salt, 70% immobilizing matrix)
  3. The properties of the waste form (thermal conductivity, melting point)
  4. The time between spent salt discharge from the reactor and its immobilization in a disposable waste form.

As such, our study seeks to explore the impact of some of these parameters as they relate to the waste form peak temperature, which must be kept below a certain limit in order to prevent melting. Our main parameters of interest are:

  • The thermal conductivity of the waste form
  • The peak temperature limit we apply to prevent melting
  • The heat generation rate (W) in the waste form.

Note that heat generation rate is a function of (1) time between spent fuel salt discharge and immobilization: because of radioactive decay, the waste heat generation decreases exponentially over time. Technically, all of the above parameters are also a function of waste form loading, meaning the relative amounts of waste and immobilizing matrix in the waste form mixture. A waste form with 50% salt, 50% matrix will have higher heat per volume and a different thermal conductivity than a waste form with 25% salt, 75% matrix. The waste form loading depends on the matrix.

In the following cells, I've set up some calculations for you to perform. You'll need to fill in values with data (decay heat, thermal conductivity, etc), run the calculations, and plot the results. Then, we'll talk about what they mean!

But first, a quick note about decay heat and waste loading The decay heat values I gave you are in W but are for the total mass of waste fuel salt discharged from a reactor generating 100 GWe-y of electricity (GWe-y is "gigawatt-electric-years"); in reality, that's "W/100GWe-y", which is not all that helpful for us. What we really need for our calculations is W/canister. To get that, we need to know (a) how much waste salt was generated to product 100 GWe-y and (b) how much waste salt goes into each canister.

The answer to part (a) is easy: 724.4 t of discharged spent fuel, not including the salt carrier (per Appendix B of the "Fuel Cycle Evaluation and Screening Study"). With that, we can do q_original (W/100GWe-y) 100 GWe-y / 724.4 t 1 t / 1000 kg = q_per_unit_mass (W/kg). Note that this is kg spent fuel materials (fuel, fission and decay products) and ignores any carrier salt also discharged. We can ignore the salt carrier - let's assume it's distilled away prior to waste form preparation.

Now, we need to know how much waste salt is put into a single waste canister. This is a tricky question. First, recall that the waste salts need to be mixed with immobilizing matrix. How much is appropriate to mix? 10%? 25%? 50%? Second, what's the density of that mixture? We've got a canister volume to fill. These things are not known to us. Let's skip all of this by making an assumption - let's assume 500 kg of waste will go into a canister. That was approximately the optimum result from the case study in Ahn's 2006 linear programming paper. The rest of the space in the canister will be immobilization matrix. We don't know what that means for waste loading, but this drastically simplifies our work.

With that, we can take the total heating rate in the table I gave you and apply both steps to get a value per canister (as a function of time!):

q_original (W/100GWe-y) 100/724.4 (GWe-y/t) 1/1000 (t/kg) * 500 (kg/canister = q_per_canister (W/canister)

Evaluating this for every time point in the data will give us a canister decay heat curve.
